<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="1257" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1257">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.512/403.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Vice Consul <persName type="to">Silliman</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-22">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 22, 1914</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your August 19. Bring to attention of General Carranza following language
                            in quoted instructions from Señor Bonillas: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>With the understanding that no payment made to officer of the
                                    Huerta Government since March 1st, 1913, is valid.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p rend="flushleft">and state that the Department assumes that this apparent
                            disregard of the right of American citizens and other foreigners, under
                            the principles international law, to pay taxes to persons exercising de
                            facto authority does not have General Carrana’s concurrence and that
                            upon having the matter called to his attention he will take appropriate
                            action.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>